Housekeeping Monitor this KB and&nbsp;ICM 574227611: Security: Zero-day vulnerability discovered by Opatch allows capture of NTLM credential on all version of Windows in early December 2024 Case owners:&nbsp;add 1 entry to the discussion section of ICM&nbsp;574227611&nbsp;for each related case you own including (1.) case #: (2.) case title (3.) customer problem statement (4.) current case severity (5.) what you need to unblock your customer  What you can share with customers in the context of an assisted support case:&nbsp;


  On Wednesday, December 4, 2024, Opatch notified Microsoft about&nbsp;a zero-day vulnerability that allows an attacker to obtain a user's NTLM credentials by having the user view a malicious file downloaded from the attackers web page in Windows Explorer.&nbsp;On Thursday, December 5th, 2024,&nbsp;Opatch published a public-facing blog post on&nbsp;File NTLM Hash Disclosure Vulnerability (0day) - and Free Micropatches for itMicrosoft developers are actively investigating the nature of this vulnerability claim and whether additional mitigations are required.&nbsp;This investigation will require time and focus.&nbsp;Until Microsoft completes their internal investigation, administrators should implement long-standing best practices from the NTLM playbook, including:&nbsp; Configure strong, hard-to-guess passwords on user accounts. Enable NTLM relay protections in your computing environment including&nbsp; SMB Signing LDAP signing LDAPS Channel Binding ADCS Channel Binding  Application developers should replace calls for NTLM with&nbsp;Negotiate, which will try to authenticate with Kerberos and only fall back to NTLM when necessary. For more information, see the NTLM section of&nbsp;Resources for deprecated features. Disabling NTLM directly halts this vulnerability.&nbsp;   

  For Microsoft case owners and account teams to know but NOT share outside of Microsoft for ANY reason including with NDA customers, OEMs or partnersThe WSD and Feature dev teams in partnership with the MSRC teams are actively investigating if this vulnerability represents a legitimate security issue or not.&nbsp;The vulnerability relies on by-design behavior within the NTLM protocol intended to provide Single Sign-On capabilities for Windows environments. NTLM NEVER sends passwords or hashes of passwords over the wire. Instead, it executes a cryptographic operation against random data using the password as a key. Attackers then use password guessing attacks to predict weak passwords from that information. Users with strong passwords are NOT affected by these types of attacks. Additionally, Microsoft has deprecated the use of NTLM within Windows and recommends customers disable it in their environments as we work to remove it from the product in future feature or quality updates.&nbsp;  Track related bugs. Install corrective or preventative OS versions or OS updates as they become available&nbsp; OS  Bug #  Resolving KB  Release Date  Comments  Windows 11 24H2 / WS 2025 (Ge)  &nbsp;55383327&nbsp;  KB5051987  2025 2B&nbsp;  &nbsp;  Server OS 23H2 (Zn)  &nbsp;55383325&nbsp;  KB5051980  2025 2B  &nbsp;  Windows 11 SV2 22H2  &nbsp;55383324&nbsp; KB5051989&nbsp; 2025 2B&nbsp; &nbsp;  Windows Server 2022  &nbsp;55383322  KB5051979  2025 2B&nbsp;  &nbsp;  Windows 10 21H2 + 22H2  &nbsp;55383321  KB5051974  2025 2B&nbsp;  &nbsp;  1809 \ RS5 \ Windows Server 2019  &nbsp;55383320  KB5052000  2025 2B&nbsp;  &nbsp;  1607 \ RS1 \ Windows Server 2016  &nbsp;55383319  KB5052006  2025 2B&nbsp;  &nbsp;&nbsp;  Windows 10 RTM  &nbsp;55383318  KB5052040  2025 2B&nbsp;  &nbsp;&nbsp;  Windows Server 2012 R2  &nbsp;55383316  KB5052042  2025 2B&nbsp;&nbsp;  &nbsp;&nbsp;   &lt;Ph&gt;

