   The Microsoft OpenSSH development team is fully aware of the existence of the following OpenSSH CVEs and the mitigation of same by OpenBSD in OpenSSH-Portable versions 6.8p1 to 9.9p1 and 9.5p1 to 9.9p1 (inclusive) depending on the CVE:&nbsp; CVE-2025-26465&nbsp;allows an active machine-in-the-middle attack (MITM) on the OpenSSH client if the VerifyHostKeyDNS option is enabled.   CVE-2025-26466 affects both the OpenSSH client and server.&nbsp;   The Microsoft MSRC team has evaluated the risk profile of both CVEs and assigned a &quot;Moderate&quot; severity, in line with the public &quot;Medium&quot; CVSS scores. The Microsoft development team is currently evaluating when an updated version of OpenSSH will release and will notify the owner of your case when that fix ships in a future Windows Update.&nbsp; &nbsp; In the meantime, the following mitigations are available for OpenSSH for Windows: For the ssh client, disable VerifyHostKeyDNS, as is default.&nbsp; For the ssh server, since&nbsp;PerSourcePenalties is not yet available in version 9.5, LoginGraceTime be reduced from its default value of 120 seconds to limit the amount of time during which pre-auth SSH2_MSG_PING packets can be sent.&nbsp;     

