solution:
The rollout of JSON AD domain extension version&nbsp;1.3.13 has been halted by marking it as Internal&nbsp; Workaround:&nbsp;Impacted customers should review the accounts used to join to the domain, and ensure they are active, do not have expired passwords, and are not locked.Customers can review the current configuration used by the extension to join the domain using this AZ CLI command: az vm extension show -g RG1--vm-name VM1  In cases where credentials have NOT changed, it's possible to re-run the extension and rejoin the domain using this AZ CLI command: az vm extension set --resource-group &quot;RG1&quot; --vm-name &quot;VM1&quot; --name JsonADDomainExtension --force-update&nbsp;  In the case credentials have changed (i.e. an updated password), or if the previous step is unsuccessful, customers can attempt to manually rejoin the domain. Customers should attempt to remove the extension and join the machines to the domain manually. Removing the extension can be done using the following AZ CLI command: az vm extension delete --resource-group &quot;RG1&quot; --vm-name &quot;VM1&quot; --name JsonADDomainExtension&nbsp;    &lt;ph&gt;  Mitigation steps published as of 2024-09-20 4:22:14 PM (CDT) on Active - Virtual Machines, Domain Connectivity Issues&nbsp;(superseded)  


  What happened?  Starting at approximately 03:12 UTC on 13 September 2024, a subset of customers may have begun to experience Virtual Machines across multiple regions disconnecting from their domains due to an extension that re-executed an older sequence number.   What do we know so far?    We determined an issue with version 1.3.13 of the &quot;Microsoft.Compute.JsonADDomainExtension&quot; extension that is causing some Virtual Machines to be disconnected from their domains.   During the upgrade process from version 1.3.11 to version 1.3.13, an unjoin and rejoin of the domain occurs. Our investigation shows this was causing issues on a subset of VMs where the domain join password has expired, or the account that's used to join is expired or disabled.     How did we respond?03:12 UTC on 13 September 2024 - Earliest report of a customer experiencing domain disconnection issues. 12:50 UTC on 19 September 2024 - Earliest customer report detected by Compute Extensions team, triggering our initial investigation in the customer issue. 07:30 UTC on 20 September 2024 - We identified the unhealthy version of the JSON AD domain extension (version 1.3.13) as the primary contributor to VMs disconnecting from domains and paused the rollout of the unhealthy update, preventing additional impact from occurring. 15:40 UTC on 20 September 2024 - We began communicating self-mitigation steps to customers, which evolved throughout the event, including alternative actions and how to determine affected resources.   Recovery steps and guidance:   This script can be used to determine affected resources. Note - this looks for all versions of the JsonADDomainExtension:  


  &nbsp;# Get all the VMs in the subscription$vms = az vm list --query &quot;[].{name:name, resourceGroup:resourceGroup}&quot; -o json | ConvertFrom-Json# Loop through each VM to check its extensionsforeach ($vm in $vms) {&nbsp; $vmName = $vm.name&nbsp; $resourceGroup = $vm.resourceGroup
# Get the list of extensions for the VM&nbsp; $extensions = az vm extension list --vm-name $vmName --resource-group $resourceGroup -o json | ConvertFrom-Json&nbsp;# Filter extensions for JsonADDomainExtension&nbsp; foreach ($ext in $extensions) {&nbsp; &nbsp; if ($ext.typePropertiesType -eq &quot;JsonADDomainExtension&quot; -and $ext.provisioningState -eq &quot;Failed&quot;) {&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Write-Output &quot;VM Name: $vmName, Resource Group: $resourceGroup&quot;&nbsp; &nbsp; }&nbsp; }}

  Impacted customers should review the accounts used to join to the domain, and ensure they are active, do not have expired passwords, and are not locked.  Get extensions on a VM to get the extension name used for JsonADDDomainExtension: 


  az vm extension list -g RG1 --vm-name VM1&nbsp;

  Customers can review the current configuration used by the extension to join the domain using this AZ CLI command: 


  az vm extension show -g RG1 --vm-name VM1 --name [extension]&nbsp;

   In the event the credentials have not changed, it's possible to re-run the extension and rejoin the domain using this AZ CLI command: 


  az vm extension set --resource-group &quot;RG1&quot; --vm-name &quot;VM1&quot; --name JsonADDomainExtension --force-update --publisher Microsoft.Compute&nbsp;

  In the case of credentials that have changed since the VM was last joined to the domain (i.e. an updated password), or if the previous step is unsuccessful, customers can attempt to manually rejoin the domain. To continue using the extension, customers can delete and re-add the extension with updated credentials.  Removing the extension can be done using the following AZ CLI command: 


  az vm extension delete --resource-group &quot;RG1&quot; --vm-name &quot;VM1&quot; --name [extension]&nbsp;

   To re-add the extension: 


  az vm extension set \&nbsp;--resource-group&nbsp;--vm-name&nbsp;--name JsonADDomainExtension \&nbsp;--publisher Microsoft.Compute \&nbsp;--version 1.3 \&nbsp;--settings '{&quot;Name&quot;: &quot;domain.com&quot;, &quot;OUPath&quot;: &quot;OU=YourOU,DC=domain,DC=com&quot;, &quot;User&quot;: &quot;domain\\username&quot;, &quot;Restart&quot;: &quot;true&quot;}' \&nbsp;--protected-settings '{&quot;Password&quot;: &quot;your-password&quot;}&nbsp;



